<div class="container">
    <section>
        <h2>Welcome to the amazing world of 3D printing!</h2>
        <p>Have you ever wondered how objects are created from almost nothing? With 3D printing, it's possible to make everything from toys to tools and even food! Let's dive into how this exciting technology works and explore some cool examples.</p>
        <!-- Add image of 3D printer here -->
        <img src="path_to_3d_printer_image" alt="3D Printer in action">
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>What is 3D Printing?</h2>
        <p>Imagine building a house out of LEGO bricks, but instead of stacking bricks, a 3D printer creates an object by adding one thin layer at a time. This process is called <strong>additive manufacturing</strong> because you add layers to make the final product.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Designing the Object:</strong> It all starts with a blueprint called a <strong>CAD (Computer-Aided Design) file</strong>. This file can be made using special software or by scanning a real object.</li>
            <li><strong>Slicing the Design:</strong> The 3D printer's software cuts the CAD file into thin layers, like slices of bread.</li>
            <li><strong>Printing the Layers:</strong> The printer reads each slice and uses materials like plastic, metal, or even chocolate to build the object layer by layer.</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- Add layer-by-layer illustration and CAD file example images here -->
        <img src="path_to_layer_by_layer_illustration" alt="Layer by Layer Illustration">
        <img src="path_to_CAD_file_example" alt="CAD File Example">
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Types of 3D Printing Technologies</h2>
        <p>Different 3D printers use different methods to create objects. Here are a few:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM):</strong> Uses melted plastic to create layers. It's like squeezing toothpaste out of a tube.</li>
            <li><strong>Stereolithography (SLA):</strong> Uses a UV light to harden liquid resin into solid layers.</li>
            <li><strong>Selective Laser Sintering (SLS):</strong> Uses a laser to fuse powdered materials like nylon or metal into solid layers.</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- Add FDM, SLA, and SLS process images here -->
        <img src="path_to_FDM_process_image" alt="FDM Process">
        <img src="path_to_SLA_process_image" alt="SLA Process">
        <img src="path_to_SLS_process_image" alt="SLS Process">
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Real-World Applications</h2>
        <p>3D printing isn't just for fun; it's used in many fields to make innovative products:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Medicine:</strong> Doctors are creating 3D-printed tissues and organs. Imagine printing a new heart!</li>
            <li><strong>Fashion:</strong> Designers use 3D printing to make unique jewelry and clothing.</li>
            <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> Architects print models of buildings to help visualize their designs.</li>
            <li><strong>Art and Archaeology:</strong> Artists make beautiful sculptures, and archaeologists recreate fossils and ancient artifacts.</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- Add images of 3D-printed medical implant, jewelry, building model, and art piece here -->
        <img src="path_to_medical_implant_image" alt="3D Printed Medical Implant">
